textfield.text:
Process:
We need to define a process for how to sketch trajectories (using these templates) so as to refine the design of a user experience.
textfield.annotations: r0-9 { align: left; } r10-141 { align: left; }

textfield.text:
Notes:
The lines represent the three different kinds of trajectory that need to be authored and how they converge, diverge and interleave in different ways to reflect the dynamics of an experience.
An experience designer needs ro create their own versions of these trajectory lines as a series of sketches, They might keep them abstract or give them specific shapes that match the particular shape of the experience (e.g., where there is a well defined map and path to be followed)
The circles represent key moments along these trajectories These need to be copied, filled in with details and placed at the relavant points along the lines.
Each template should come with placeholders for key metadata (e.g., name, type), instructions on how to apply it, a link to online tutorial material, and space to add design notes and relevant media.
Colour might be used to distinguish between canonical, participant and historic trajectories and their annoations
Step 1: assemble existing media that are relevant to the design and load into the sketch tool. These could include maps, photos of key locations and objects, screen designs for interfaces.
Step 2: Identify the core canonical trajectories in the experience and sketch their structures
Step 3: Consider how each of the key transitions in the framework applies to the design. Fill in the relevant transition sketches (circles) and use these to annotate the canonical trajectories

Step 4: Explore all possible combinations of canonical trajectories (including with themselves). For each, create an encounter sketch annoated with potential 'encounters', 'isolations' and 'pacing' sketches
Step 5: Sketch out possible participant trajectories in relation to your canonical ones, labeling them with divergence and convergence subsketches.

Step 6: Sketch out the historic trajectories for your experience that represent the different ways in which it can be documented and subsequently recounted. Annotate them with compleyted sub-sketches (circles) that show when and how participants document their experience. how the service provider gives them further documentation, how this is edited (selected, composed, annotated) in various ways and then how it is used for reflection or recounting the experience to others.
Step 7: publish, share or present your trajectory sketches and/or connect them back to other design materials
